{{ModId}}_Armored_Snail.Name: Armored Snail
{{ModId}}_Armored_Snail.Description: This snail absorbs iron sulfide and pyrite and uses the minerals to create the shell that protects its innards.

{{ModId}}_Bobtail_Squid.Name: Bobtail Squid
{{ModId}}_Bobtail_Squid.Description: Also known as 'dumpling squid', these smaller cephalopods propel themselves through the water with the fins on their mantle.

{{ModId}}_Brittle_Star.Name: Brittle Star
{{ModId}}_Brittle_Star.Description: Also known as 'serpent star' due to their long, snake-like arms.

{{ModId}}_Chondraster.Name: Chondraster
{{ModId}}_Chondraster.Description: When paired with Hertwigia, the two resemble an iconic duo.

{{ModId}}_Christmas_Tree_Worm.Name: Christmas Tree Worm
{{ModId}}_Christmas_Tree_Worm.Description: The two Christmas tree-like crowns that protrude from its body are used for catching food floating nearby.

{{ModId}}_Coffinfish.Name: Coffinfish
{{ModId}}_Coffinfish.Description: This species of sea toad has inflatable gills that it uses to fill its body with water.

{{ModId}}_Comb_Jelly.Name: Comb Jelly
{{ModId}}_Comb_Jelly.Description: These creatures use the colorful and comb-like plates on their body to propel themselves through the water.

{{ModId}}_Cookiecutter_Shark.Name: Cookiecutter Shark
{{ModId}}_Cookiecutter_Shark.Description: They are named after their ability to cut cookie-shaped holes out of larger animals.

{{ModId}}_Cowfish.Name: Cowfish
{{ModId}}_Cowfish.Description: Known as 'cowfish' for their box-like shape and the two horns protruding from the front of their head.

{{ModId}}_Emperor_Dumbo.Name: Emperor Dumbo
{{ModId}}_Emperor_Dumbo.Description: The king of all dumbo octopuses.

{{ModId}}_Firework_Jellyfish.Name: Firework Jellyfish
{{ModId}}_Firework_Jellyfish.Description: Not much is known about this species, except that the colors and shape of its tentacles resemble a firework burst.

{{ModId}}_Flabby_Whalefish.Name: Flabby Whalefish
{{ModId}}_Flabby_Whalefish.Description: They have a large, agape mouth fit for eating as much shellfish as they please.

{{ModId}}_Flying_Gurnard.Name: Flying Gurnard
{{ModId}}_Flying_Gurnard.Description: These creatures can use their large, wing-like pectoral fins to glide above water for short distances.

{{ModId}}_Giant_Clam.Name: Giant Clam
{{ModId}}_Giant_Clam.Description: As members of the largest living mollusks on Earth, these bivalves can weigh more than 500 pounds and reach 4 feet in length.

{{ModId}}_Giant_Isopod.Name: Giant Isopod
{{ModId}}_Giant_Isopod.Description: These mysterious crustaceans are considered an example of deep-sea gigantism due to their large size compared to their terrestrial relatives.

{{ModId}}_Giant_Tube_Worm.Name: Giant Tube Worm
{{ModId}}_Giant_Tube_Worm.Description: These worms come together to form a large and towering colony.

{{ModId}}_Grenadier.Name: Grenadier
{{ModId}}_Grenadier.Description: Specifically known as the 'onion-eye grenadier', this species uses its particularly large and bulbous eyes to help in its search for food.

{{ModId}}_Hatchetfish.Name: Hatchetfish
{{ModId}}_Hatchetfish.Description: These fish are named 'hatchetfish' after their triangular-shaped bodies.

{{ModId}}_Hertwigia.Name: Hertwigia
{{ModId}}_Hertwigia.Description: When paired with Chondraster, the two resemble an iconic duo.

{{ModId}}_Horseshoe_Crab.Name: Horseshoe Crab
{{ModId}}_Horseshoe_Crab.Description: Despite the name and how they may look, these creatures are more closely related to scorpions and spiders than they are to crabs.

{{ModId}}_Immortal_Jellyfish.Name: Immortal Jellyfish
{{ModId}}_Immortal_Jellyfish.Description: Known as 'immortal' due to their ability to reverse their life cycle.

{{ModId}}_Leaf_Sheep.Name: Leaf Sheep
{{ModId}}_Leaf_Sheep.Description: These sea slugs are widely known as 'leaf sheep' due to their cute, sheep-like faces and backs full of fluffy cerata.

{{ModId}}_Oblique_Banded_Snapper.Name: Oblique-Banded Snapper
{{ModId}}_Oblique_Banded_Snapper.Description: This fish can be recognized from other snappers by its reddish hue and striking yellow stripes.

{{ModId}}_Parrotfish.Name: Parrotfish
{{ModId}}_Parrotfish.Description: The fused teeth of this fish resemble that of a parrot beak.

{{ModId}}_Piglet_Squid.Name: Piglet Squid
{{ModId}}_Piglet_Squid.Description: This small squid lives in deep depths of around 320ft.

{{ModId}}_Pocket_Shark.Name: Pocket Shark
{{ModId}}_Pocket_Shark.Description: These small sharks have a pocket gland located above each of their pectoral fins. It's theorized that these glands release either pheromones or bioluminescent fluids.

{{ModId}}_Pygmy_Seahorse.Name: Pygmy Seahorse
{{ModId}}_Pygmy_Seahorse.Description: The bumps all over the body of these creatures are calcium-rich and allow them to camouflage among the fan corals they live in.

{{ModId}}_Pygmy_Shark.Name: Pygmy Shark
{{ModId}}_Pygmy_Shark.Description: The pygmy shark is the second-smallest of all shark species, right after the dwarf lanternshark.

{{ModId}}_Red_Lipped_Batfish.Name: Red-Lipped Batfish
{{ModId}}_Red_Lipped_Batfish.Description: This bottom dweller walks instead of swims and has fins that resemble legs.

{{ModId}}_Ribbon_Worm.Name: Ribbon Worm
{{ModId}}_Ribbon_Worm.Description: They shoot a proboscis out of their body in order to attack prey.

{{ModId}}_Sea_Bunny.Name: Sea Bunny
{{ModId}}_Sea_Bunny.Description: A member of the nudibranch family, these sea slugs are widely beloved for their bunny-like appearance.

{{ModId}}_Sea_Butterfly.Name: Sea Butterfly
{{ModId}}_Sea_Butterfly.Description: This elegant sea snail is also known as the 'potato chip of the sea' due to it being a food source for several different species of animals.

{{ModId}}_Sea_Pig.Name: Sea Pig
{{ModId}}_Sea_Pig.Description: A member of the deep-sea sea cucumber family, the pinkish bodies and tubular legs these creatures possess are slightly reminiscent of a pig.

{{ModId}}_Spongiforma.Name: Spongiforma
{{ModId}}_Spongiforma.Description: Fully known as 'spongiforma squarepantsii', this creature is very sponge-like in appearance but is actually a fungus.

{{ModId}}_Sunflower_Sea_Star.Name: Sunflower Sea Star
{{ModId}}_Sunflower_Sea_Star.Description: This creature is one of the largest sea stars in the world and can have a maximum arm span of 1 meter.

{{ModId}}_Tadpole.Name: Tadpole
{{ModId}}_Tadpole.Description: The aquatic larval stage of frogs and toads.

{{ModId}}_Tonguefish.Name: Tonguefish
{{ModId}}_Tonguefish.Description: Due to their small size, these fish are not usually sought after to eat.

{{ModId}}_Water_Bear.Name: Water Bear
{{ModId}}_Water_Bear.Description: The 'water bear' (tardigrade) is a microscopic, eight-legged creature that likes wet environments.

{{ModId}}_Yellowhead_Jawfish.Name: Yellowhead Jawfish
{{ModId}}_Yellowhead_Jawfish.Description: A species of jawfish that build burrows in the sand of the coral reefs they live in.
